There is little time left before 18 September, there is still no agreement between D66 and VVD about who their preferred coalition parties would be and official negotiations have not even started. After formal negotiations between parties start they still need to write a 'regeerakkoord' decide who the cabinet will be and get approved by the party members of the parties within the coalition (which will be 4 or 5 parties). Last time this process took 3 months (june 24 till oktober 26), it seems really unlikely it will take less than 4 weeks this time.

Passage of time adjustment supported by summer holidays that started 9 July and lasts until mid-August (https://bit.ly/374KRpW), recent cabinet shuffles (https://bit.ly/2ULu09k), new storm warnings (https://bit.ly/2TxAhoo), increasing Covid-19 hospital cases and disruptions resulting from recent extensive flooding in parts of Netherlands, the move to a new building for parliamentary sittings (https://bit.ly/374KRpW) and the apparent lack of progress reported by the informateur, Harme (https://bit.ly/2ULu09k) after a meeting with the King two weeks ago. All in all, many things to keep people too busy to be concerned about forming a government, while Rutte probably has little motivation to progress the formation as he's already in the top job!
Negotiations have been postponed until late August, and the fragmented nature of the Dutch government is bound to drag negotiations out.
The delay to mid august in reality only leaves two weeks of talks to come up with an agreement.

The recent elections in the Netherlands had offered the largest number of political parties since the 1940’s with a myriad of socio-political agendas in possibly the World’s total proportional representative system that has produced prolonged negotiations with the various factors to formulate a sitting administration. A childcare benefit scandal and issues over political transparency, in the midst of a global pandemic have deadlocked the process. All parties have agreed to further stall talks until mid-August when a draft proposal will be offered by Rutte and the leader of the second largest party. A firm date before September looks unlikely, although possible.

Hamers report has just been published (1). Conclusion, a 6 party coalition is currently not possible. Her advice is for VVD and D66 to start a document on main point to which the other parties can be added the second half of august. That leaves 1 month for a coalition to be concluded before 17 September.

The window for a first-bin outcome is closing quickly now. Hamer is apparently meeting with Hoekstra (CDA) and Segers (CU) for further talks today, which suggests a continuation of the former coalition has become slightly more likely and could be the dominant strategy in the government formation now in order to achieve a quick resolution of a deadlock. With all the dirt that has come to light (new: https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2021/06/cda-confirms-publishing-millionaire-gave-e1m-to-election-campaign/ ) and the Omtzigt departure, the CDA lost support dramatically in recent polls and must be happy if they avoid a new election in the first place and if they are included in a new government. However, unless there's a miracle (see Rutte III cabinet = Rutte IV cabinet) immediately, a new government will not be sworn in before Friday this week. Thus, it looks like a demissionary government will attend the next European Council meeting next week. With respect to the government formation, Hoekstra and the CDA now must be considered as the most obstructive force, which is consistent with their lost parliamentary weight in the past 2021 election, probably a good deal of miscalculation and loss of reality and their fear of being marginalized in a new government, a factor that I have previously under-estimated. Lesson learned: be more critical of and constantly question your own assumptions. Two of my baisc assumptions (1. a new government will be needed for the ORD to be approved in parliament; 2. the government formation will be concluded before the June 2021 European Council meeting) have proven false, sadly. https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2021/06/hoekstra-omtzigt-exit-will-not-make-coalition-talks-more-difficult/ @bh4eh @Anneinak

It has taken Dutch MP’s eight weeks since the 2021 election results to appoint a negotiator, Mariëtte Hamer to forge an agreement amongst the seven political parties to form a coalition government. That is two months. Her remit was to assess which parties basically agree with each other and produce a tentative coalition of politicians to write a draft agreement. She reported back on June 6 with the following information: She did not dare to say how long this would take; She HOPED that things keep going; Sees no basic content differences;

Very strange situation, as on the one hand the "Kaag option" becomes more unlikely amid Hoekstra's (CDA) remarks on a potential participation of both the PvdA and GL (which may just turn out to be bluff in order to secure a senior role of the conservative wing in an otherwise balanced coalition, imho; I wouldn't read Hoektra's wording as "ruling out" such a coalition either, it's just not his favorite option). On the other hand, the minority government of VVD, D66, CDA and CU, a perfect continuation of the sitting Rutte III cabinet and demissionary government, could be slightly more likely (despite its shortcomings with regards to their ability pushing controversial legislation through the senate) - which could in fact speed up government formation a bit, as it would take most other options and fundamental questions off the table. However, the Hamer report due 06 June 2021 is now expected by some to be published with a delay. https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2021/06/five-party-coalition-unlikely-as-cda-leader-rules-out-groenlinks-pvda-idea/

1) base rate: average duration of formation since 1946 is 94 days. Variation is large (with the last formation going on for 225 days) 2) There are several factors that would indicate a long formation a) low trust, with high profile debates on whether certain parties are ethically ok with forming a coalition with others and about openness in political culture. b) a splintering of parliament, with a record number of parties represented, making majority formation tricky 3) but also some factors that would indicate a speedy transition a) 'demissionary' status of current government b) the sense of crisis and need for a mandated government c) indications from several parties that they are not looking to make a fully negotiated coalition contract but instead will roll over significant chunks of policy making to the post-formation phase.

While Rutte & Kaag would like a government and cabinet formed by the summer recess (https://bit.ly/2QNKCv2), with Hamer, the negotiator / informateur having to meet the leaders or all 18 parties last week and thus in all likelihood having to report back to those 18 at some stage prior to the cabinet formation, as @Anneinak holds (https://bit.ly/3bTVU8l), the more people involved in negotiations, the longer the process, it seems a tight fit to get things done before the summer recess being 3rd July - 31 August (https://bit.ly/3fjS3U9), there's not a lot of time left to get this all negotiated, agreed, in writing of some sort and the government formed and sworn in; 5 weeks before the recess and in terms of this question, just over two weeks after the recess. Harmer's report is due by 6 June but; "...but she already made it clear on Friday (probably 14 May) that this is not a hard deadline for her. While she acknowledged the urgency of the recovery plan, it is more about the "quality of the work," she said at the time".
The clock is ticking and little progress has been made.
https://nltimes.nl/2021/05/17/cabinet-formation-begin-today
If I had to place a bet, I'd put my money on a coalition formed of VVD, D66, CDA, PvdA and GL, and pretty soon.

There seems to be desire on the part of D66 and VVD to form a cabinet before the summer recess but there are currently few signs of concrete progress. Talks by the informateur with all 18 parties are due to finish by 6 June but that is described as 'not a hard deadline' and is still some way off a cabinet. So I am shifting my estimate up for the second two bins and down for the first.

"Talks on forming a new cabinet must now speed up to ensure there is a government as soon as possible, the main party leaders say, after exchanging views with Mariette Hamer, who is leading the negotiations. In particular the VVD, D66 and CDA – all part of the present cabinet – are calling for more speed. ‘I do not think the Netherlands will understand it if things take much longer,’ prime minister Mark Rutte said after his meeting with Hamer on Tuesday. [...] D66 leader Sigrid Kaag said after her meeting with Hamer that there should be a new cabinet before the summer recess. ‘That is our ambition and our approach,’ she told reporters. ‘We want a cabinet that is as stable and progressive as possible,’ she said, adding that GroenLinks, the PvdA, VVD and CDA are potential partners." https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2021/05/main-parties-call-for-speed-in-putting-together-a-new-coalition-government/
There seems to be concern that there won't be a government sworn in by the summer recess (which is early July), so allocating more heavily towards the second bucket.

The arguments that are shaping my thinking are 1) that Hamer's report is due June 6th, only 11 days before the first bin closes, 2) the article I read said there will not be a new government "in the short term", 3) Rutte is wounded, 4) Omzigt is lurking, 5) Willink recommended against the new negotiator being someone political like Hamer 6) Anne's basic rule: the more parties there are to a negotiation, the longer it takes. This coalition may involve 4 or 5 parties! 7) Why would it take less time than it took the last time???

Have completely revised this following news of a no confidence vote in Mark Rutte. If he is forced to resign I think it highly likely it will take until after 18 SEP to form a govt but I think resignation unlikely as he has no obvious candidates to succeed him and . I give resignation a +10% chance of happening but 90% that it would take until after 18 SEP so 9%. If he stays I now estimate there is a 25-65-10 distribution over the three bins, so multiplying by .9 gives the estimates above.
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-netherlands-politics-rutte/ruttes-prospects-of-forming-new-government-wane-as-coalition-partner-quits-idUSKBN2BQ07R blijf kijken....
Rutte has been severely damaged and all major parties have shown disapproval. It would require a serious about-face to now wrap up a government within 90 days

It appears that Rutte has been caught out being 'economic with the truth' during the negotiations to form a government - https://reut.rs/3dwhekb. That has potentially delayed the process of forming the new coalition government. Probably only by a few weeks so for the time being, I will hold my above position. The need to form a government as quickly as possible is pressing. As @SE_Meyer pointed out, the next EU Council meeting is 24/25 June and as a founding member of the EU, it would not reflect well on Netherlands to have an empty seat at the table. Equally pressing is the need to approve the EU ORD amendment in order to release the NGEU covid recovery funds to the countries of the EU. Thus, albeit Sigrid Kaag of D66 commented that if she were Rutte, she would not continue seeking to form a coaltion around Rutte's winning vote in the light of this information, Rutte is an experienced and shrewd politician. As @tarun_b suggested to @Anneinak , Rutte knows how to get out of tricky situations. As indeed happened today with his escape from a vote of no confidence (https://bit.ly/3rLIZKL). That said, it is worth bearing in mind that Rutte's last government was forced to resign because of some rather underhand tactics by the tax office about child benefits (https://bit.ly/3mdRWeG) so one would not be remiss in questioning his honesty. Nonetheless, the Dutch voters gave him the most votes amongst many parties that stood in the election in March 2021. He must have some redeeming qualities.

https://www.reuters.com/article/us-netherlands-politics-rutte-vote/dutch-pm-rutte-censured-but-survives-no-confidence-vote-idUSKBN2BP04Z Once the fallout has fallen out, this may become clearer. Stay tuned.

The next European Council meeting will happen on 24/25 June 2021, it would be neat to have a full Netherlands government with a mandate by their parliament to support decisions, and represent their country as an important founding member. It would also be neat if the cabinet is appointed as a whole in time so that the government is up and running well before the Council, and is well-informed about the agenda and is able to influence agenda and decisions even in the weeks ahead. https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/meetings/european-council/2021/06/24-25/

Shifted slightly towards the shortest timescale but only slightly. There is clearly a desire to form a cabinet quickly, by 'the summer'. However it looks like there will still need to be a 4 party coalition so could require some time for negotiations to complete. The same coalition as last time could work but the number of seats won is different so there will need to be a reallocation of posts which could take time. I return to the fact that only 11 out the last 20 coalitions have taken less than 90 days, some factors involved in the longest formations are not present (eg last time irreconcilable differences between GroneLinks and the Christian parties; GroneLinks have not done well this time so unlikely to be involved) so I put the third bin down to only 2%; I think 90 days likely - but far from certain.

It's interesting that D66 came first in both Amsterdam and Rotterdam, so the liberal left-leaning party's ascend clearly is an urban phenomenon. It's also interesting that even the Netherlands as a rather small, compact nation obviously have a rural - urban, likely old- young divide with respect to politics. This indicates that the D66 will want to play a much more important role in the upcoming government, which rocks the boat a bit, and it's pretty obvious there's no real way around the D66 for the VVD, unless they are about to forge a coalition of eight or so. On the other hand, D66 is not strong enough to lead a government themselves: even if they could forge a new movement of all other parties (and the one independent candidate) except for VVD, PVV, CDA, FvD and CU, they'd fail a majority with just 71 seats. D66 + CDA and six more parties would sum 77 seats, but even this is rather unrealistic at this point in time. The most viable solution seems to be a centrist government of VVD (34 seats), CDA (15; both conservative), D66 (24) plus either PvdA (9) or the green GroenLinks (8), which both seem to keep a balance of 2/3 conservative, 1/3 progressive - no hardliners and pragmatism before party politics -, which could in general achieve good results in terms of government projects and even reflect the will of electorate. I think it's rather a matter of details now, and 73 seats for the three most heavy weight-parties are a good precondition for a limited ambition of a fourth junior coalition partner that sees the necessity to support this mix of government politics.

During the last 20 elections dating back to 1952 the cabinet has formed within 90 days 11 times (55%), within 182 days 7 times (35%), and twice over 182 days. I used this as a base rate but moved slightly towards the lower end because a) polling shows we could get a two-party coalition which is likely to take less time to form and b) after the extensive discussions in 2017 some potential blind alleys will be avoided this time. However even some 2-party coalitions have taken some time to form so there is still some room for uncertainty.

Following poll data (https://www.politico.eu/europe-poll-of-polls/netherlands/), it is highly likely that a multi-party coalition needs to be formed with at least four parties given that Rutte will be able to secure largest win and leader of the government. Since the current government coalition may have a slight edge, it is likely that the same coalition will continue their work. Therefore, I expect deliberations to be long in comparison to other European countries, but shorter than for the last government, since a notion of urgency on account of the COVID-crisis will surely be felt by all actors.
